// place-castle.ipt
// =====================================================================
// A castle / keep / fortified seat of power. Purely institutional —
// NO commerce, no priced stock. A GM gets: the ruler and their
// disposition, the castle's type and condition, the garrison, notable
// features and defences, another power at court, and a current
// situation to drive intrigue.
//
// Entry table: [@TF-Castle]
//
// Inputs (optional, via API promptValues):
//   prompt1 town  /  prompt2 shopType (display)  /  prompt3 shopName
//
// Reuses people.ipt for the ruler and court figures. No prices.ipt —
// you don't shop at a castle.

Title: Castle
Use: people.ipt

Prompt: town {} an unnamed town
Prompt: shopType {} castle
Prompt: shopName {}
Prompt: keeperName {}
Prompt: keeperRace {}
Prompt: keeperGender {}
Prompt: keeperAge {}
Prompt: keeperDesc {}

Table: TF-Castle
Set: town={$prompt1}
Set: passedName={$prompt3}
Set: ruler=[when]{$keeperName}=[do][@PersonName][else]{$keeperName}[end]
Set: ranc=[when]{$keeperRace}=[do][@Ancestry][else]{$keeperRace}[end]
Set: rulerdsc=[when]{$keeperDesc}=[do][@PersonDesc][else]{$keeperDesc}[end]
Set: title=[@RulerTitle]
**[@CastleTitle]** *(seat of power above {$town})*\n&
**[@CastleType], [@CastleCondition]**\n&
**Ruler:** {$title} {$ruler}, a {$rulerdsc} {$ranc} who is [@RulerDisposition].\n&
**Garrison:** [@Garrison]\n&
**Defences & features:** [@CastleFeature]; [@CastleFeature]\n&
**Power behind the throne:** [@CourtFigure]\n&
**Right now:** [@CastleSituation]

Table: CastleTitle
[when]{$passedName}=[do][@CastleName][else]{$passedName}[end]

// Castle name: by feature, by founder, or by the town.
Table: CastleName
[@CastleNameWord] [@CastleNameSuffix]
[@FamilyName] [@CastleNameSuffix]
The [@CastleNameAdj] [@CastleNameSuffix]

Table: CastleNameWord
Raven
Storm
Grey
Iron
High
Black
Wolf
Thorn
Wind
Dragon

Table: CastleNameAdj
Old
Broken
Crooked
Last
Silent
Bright
Frozen

Table: CastleNameSuffix
Keep
Hold
Castle
Tower
Watch
Spire
Garrison
Bastion

Table: RulerTitle
Lord
Lady
Baron
Baroness
Count
Countess
Castellan
Knight-Commander
the Dowager
Warden

Table: CastleType
A squat, thick-walled border keep built for war
A sprawling noble castle with gardens and a great hall
A lonely watchtower-and-wall guarding a mountain pass
An old motte-and-bailey of timber and earthworks
A grand fortress-palace, seat of a powerful house
A converted monastery, now garrisoned and gated

Table: CastleCondition
in fine repair, banners snapping in the wind
showing its age, with scaffolding on one tower
recently besieged — the scars are still raw
half-ruined, with only the keep still held
freshly fortified, new stone bright against the old
quietly crumbling while its lord pretends otherwise

Table: RulerDisposition
just but cold, and utterly inflexible about the law
generous to friends and merciless to enemies
distracted by debts and pretending all is well
ambitious, with eyes on a larger seat than this
beloved by the smallfolk and resented by peers
old, tired, and clinging to a fraying grip on power
paranoid, seeing plots in every shadow (perhaps rightly)
charming in public and ruthless behind closed doors

Table: Garrison
{!g=={20+2d20}}roughly {$g} soldiers under [@PersonName], [@GarrisonState]

Table: GarrisonState
a grizzled, competent captain who runs a tight watch
a green officer out of their depth and knowing it
a captain whose loyalty is quietly for sale
a fanatically loyal commander devoted to the ruler
a captain feuding openly with the castellan
veterans bored stiff by years of uneventful peace

Table: CastleFeature
a deep dry moat crossed by a single drawbridge
a portcullis that hasn't been raised in living memory
murder-holes and arrow-slits covering every approach
a hidden sally-port known only to the garrison
a crumbling section of wall the lord can't afford to fix
a tall signal-beacon kept laid and ready
dungeons rumoured to hold more than common criminals
a deep well and stores enough for a long siege
a great hall hung with the trophies of past wars
a rookery of messenger birds, constantly coming and going

Table: CourtFigure
{!c==[@PersonName]}{!canc==[@Ancestry]}{$c}, a [@PersonDesc] {$canc} — [@CourtRole], [@CourtMotive]

Table: CourtRole
the steward who truly runs the place
the ruler's spymaster, officially "an advisor"
a visiting envoy who has overstayed their welcome
the heir, impatient for a seat not yet vacant
the court mage, indispensable and unsettling
the ruler's confessor and closest confidant
a hostage-guest of noble birth, watched closely

Table: CourtMotive
loyal, but with a price everyone forgets they have
quietly working against the ruler's interests
honestly devoted and increasingly worried
playing two factions against each other for profit
hiding a secret that could topple the household
simply trying to keep the whole place from collapsing

Table: CastleSituation
a raven arrived this morning and the ruler has been grim since
the garrison is on quiet alert, though no one will say why
an honoured guest is expected within the day, and nerves are high
a servant has gone missing and the household is being searched
two factions at court are one insult away from open conflict
the ruler is ill, and the question of succession hangs unspoken
a prisoner in the dungeon has asked, specifically, for adventurers
envoys from a rival house are at the gate, uninvited
the lord is hiring discreet swords for a matter not spoken of openly
old debts have come due and a creditor's agent waits in the hall

// Standalone name roll (collision-proof, for note titles etc.).
Table: TF-CastleName
[@CastleName]
